      "side": 1,
      "message": "Thinking out loud: here `Lease` struct serves 3 purposes:\n  input for desired lease\n  actual datastore entity\n  lease handle for users (essentially tuple of (AssetID,Number) for Terminate call\n\nAs a user, I don\u0027t like this because it\u0027s not clear what I should set for Apply to work w/o reading Apply() code, especially why is there \"duration\" arg alongside ExpirationTime.\nAs a user, I\u0027d prefer:\n\n    // Each arg is required here, no need to read the docs or code.\n    // Luckily, each arg has different type, so callsites won\u0027t be ambiguous.\n    //   If it wasn\u0027t the case, a new input args, would have been ideal.\n    //\n    // *Lease is returned on both success and errConflict\n    func Apply(ctx, asset, leasee, payload, duration) (*Lease, error)\n    type Lease struct {\n      AssetID, Leasee, ...\n      // possibly other private fields only to support 2 funcs below\n    }\n    func (*Lease) Terminate(ctx) error\n    func (*Lease) Extend(ctx, duration) error // if necessary\n\n\nFor non-internal package, I\u0027d probably even create a separate `leaseDS` struct which takes care of ds put/get in order to avoid committing to a specific DS layout due to public Lease struct. \n\nHowever, we have an additional need: Apply must work as part of a bigger transaction.\n\nIn fact, it\u0027d be nice to batch reading existing Lease with other reads at the beginning of a transaction, and similarly writing new lease entity together with other written entities. So, having ds entity Lease{} public is actually good for us.\n\n\u003d\u003d\u003d end of thinking \u003d\u003d\u003d\n\n\nSo, the main AI is support Apply within transaction.\n\n\nOne of possible approaches: split off half of Apply into \n  // TODO: shorter name\n  // Just returns a Lease to datastore.Put at caller\u0027s discretion.\n  func ApplyISwearExistingLeaseExpireOrNotExists(transCtx, \u003cnormal apply arguments\u003e) *Lease\n  \nThen RunManager/ProjectManager code would then need to write some boilerplate, but so far I don\u0027t know how to avoid it:\n\nl :\u003d \u0026lease.Lease{AssetID: aid1}\n\nerr :\u003d ds.runInTransasaction(ctx, func(ctx) error {\n  ..\n  dsBatcher.register(l, func(err) error {\n    // copy-paste switch from inside Apply() func 😞\n    switch{\n    case err\u003d\u003ddatastore.ErrNoSuchEntity: \n      l \u003d nil\n    case err !\u003dnil:\n      return annotate....\n    }\n    return nil\n  })\n  ...\n  err :\u003d dsBatcher.Get(ctx)\n  ...\n  \n  if l \u003d\u003d nil || l.Expired() { // can acquire lease\n    l \u003d lease.ApplyISwearExistingLeaseExpiredOrNotExists(ctx, aid1, \"mine!\", ...)\n    dsBatcher.register(l, func (err) error {\n      l \u003d nil\n      return errors.Annotate(err, \"failed to put new Lease for asset %s\", aid1).Tag(transient.Tag).Err()\n    })\n  }\n  return ds.Put(ctx)\n})\nif err !\u003d nil { ... // trans failed }\n\nif l !\u003d nil {\n  // I got a lease on asset1 until l.ExpirationTime.\n}",
